BASIC TABLE CREATION AND QUERIES:

open command line client

create table products( 
    id int, 
    name varchar(50), 
    description varchar(100), 
    price float, 
    quantity int
);

show tables;

describe products;

insert into products values(1, 'laptop', 'HP Victus', 70000, 5);

select id, name, quantity from products;


'''


'''
SQL DATA TYPES REFERENCE:

=== NUMERIC TYPES ===
INT              - Standard integer (-2147483648 to 2147483647)
BIGINT           - Large integer (-9223372036854775808 to 9223372036854775807)
SMALLINT         - Small integer (-32768 to 32767)
TINYINT          - Very small integer (0 to 255)
DECIMAL(p, s)    - Fixed-point (p=total digits, s=decimal places) e.g., DECIMAL(10, 2)
FLOAT            - Single precision floating-point
DOUBLE           - Double precision floating-point
NUMERIC          - Similar to DECIMAL

EXAMPLE:
CREATE TABLE products (
    product_id INT,
    price DECIMAL(10, 2),
    rating FLOAT
);

=== STRING TYPES ===
VARCHAR(n)       - Variable-length string (max n characters)
CHAR(n)          - Fixed-length string (padded with spaces)
TEXT             - Large text (up to 65535 characters)
LONGTEXT         - Very large text (up to 4GB)
ENUM             - List of allowed values
SET              - Multiple values from predefined list

EXAMPLE:
CREATE TABLE users (
    username VARCHAR(50),
    email VARCHAR(100),
    bio TEXT,
    status ENUM('active', 'inactive', 'suspended')
);

=== DATE AND TIME TYPES ===
DATE             - Date only (YYYY-MM-DD)
TIME             - Time only (HH:MM:SS)
DATETIME         - Date and time (YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS)
TIMESTAMP        - Timestamp (auto-updates to current time)
YEAR             - Year only (YYYY)

EXAMPLE:
CREATE TABLE orders (
    order_id INT,
    order_date DATE,
    created_at DATETIME,
    updated_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
);

=== BOOLEAN TYPE ===
BOOLEAN or BOOL  - True (1) or False (0)

EXAMPLE:
CREATE TABLE features (
    feature_id INT,
    is_active BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE
);

=== BINARY TYPES ===
BINARY(n)        - Fixed-length binary data
VARBINARY(n)     - Variable-length binary data
BLOB             - Binary Large Object

=== SPECIAL TYPES ===
JSON             - JSON data structure
UUID             - Universally Unique Identifier (as VARCHAR(36) or CHAR(36))

EXAMPLE WITH PRODUCTS TABLE:
CREATE TABLE products (
    id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
    name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
    description VARCHAR(100),
    price DECIMAL(10, 2) NOT NULL,
    quantity INT DEFAULT 0,
    created_at DATETIME DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    is_available BOOLEAN DEFAULT TRUE
);

INSERT INTO products VALUES(
    1, 
    'laptop', 
    'HP Victus', 
    70000.00, 
    5,
    NOW(),
    TRUE
);

SELECT * FROM products;

'''



